[00:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'A bonsai tree is a full-sized tree. Same DNA, same structure, same capability. Just grown in a way that takes up almost no space. That is exactly what Prism ML has done with image generation. They'

[00:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'took Flux, one of the best open-source image generation models available today, and they asked a simple but radical question. What if, instead of storing every weight in the model as a precise'

[00:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'floating-point number, you just stored -1, 0, or +1? Three choices. That is it. They called it Bonsai Image 4 Billion, and today we are'

[00:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'running it locally. This is Fahad Mirza, and I welcome you to the channel. You can see that we have been covering these bonsai models for quite some time now, and they have been evolving pretty'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'nicely. And now they have afforded into this image modality. So, I\'m quite curious to see what sort of images they generate. If you go to their GitHub repo, they have shared some of the samples and some'

[01:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of the commands which I\'m going to test out. So, let\'s get right into it. And as a bonus, I\'m going to also unpack what exactly is meant by all of these terminologies like two-bit, one-bit,'

[01:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ternary, binary, and how they are different from the actual full-precision models. I\'m going to use this Ubuntu system. So, let me quickly install uh my virtual environment, and then we will go from'

[01:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there. And now let me get clone the repo, and I will drop the link to it in video\'s description. And now let me run the setup, which installs all the prerequisites,'

[01:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'everything. While that happens, let me take you to this diagram where we try to understand how exactly this model is different. Remember what I said about the three values, -1, 0, and +1? Look at the'

[01:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'middle panel here. Those four cells are four weights from the transformer. Each one is just a direction, positive or negative or zero. Now look at that small box underneath'

[02:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'them that says FP16 scale. Now, for every 128 weights, there is one full precision number that gives the whole group its magnitude.'

[02:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That is the whole trick. You\'re not throwing away the scale of the model. You are just forcing every individual weight to pick a side. And that single decision takes you from'

[02:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'around 7.7 GB down to just 1.21 GB. Look at those size bars at the bottom of the diagram. The purple bar is full flux. The teal bar is ternary bonsai. That is how much'

